@Mike
My approach is the molar opposite.

(Hope I don't catch too much plaque over it)

@Francis

Oh, and also, the THC.  But that's pretty recent, so it's mostly the archives. And the alcohol.

I shouldn't have admitted that.  Now I'll never get to be the Secretary of "War" or the FBI Director.

@Bob

Some previous clues include sponsoring book fairs, collaborating with MADD (Mothers Against Drunk Driving), field trip planning, etc.  

Or did you mean every time it's clued?

@Mean Old Lady

Also in previous clues:  sponsoring read-a-thons and walkathons, putting on school carnivals, an child support in general.

And a few reference being hypocritical (as in Harper Valley).

@Vaer
Then one must be her own proof-reader, methinks.  Or run spell-check (though it won't flag typos that are real words.)
And when someone has a little punny fun with such an error, we should just enjoy it....

@Andrzej

Indeed, people do shorten appetizer to APP. 

Why waste time pronouncing four whole syllables, when you could just pronounce one and get your spinach artichoke dip that much faster!? 😏

@Andrzej

Daily Mail delivery is still a thing here. How much any one person receives depends on what they’ve opted to receive digitally. But junk mail, in the form of circulars, solicitations and the like, is always there to pick up the slack.

At least 90% of my daily mail delivery goes straight into the trash.

@Heidi, @Andrzej

Junk mail in the US is really outrageous. Every summer when I visit dear old mum, I'm shocked and angered at the amount of junk that goes in the trash daily. And after being away for a month I return to Yokohama and an empty mailbox.

Is it only the US that has such a problem?

@Andrzej

Strong regulations?  

Then you have no freedom.  Why shouldn't companies be free to bury you in unwanted garbage?

@Andrzej
We have postal delivery 6 days a week, not long ago it was twice a day. If you read eg Sherlock Holmes it mentions deliveries in London up to 10 times a day. Many people wrote a lot, hence there are huge volumes of authors' letters published. 

I get junk and a few other things; bank cards get delivered. But there are lots of parcels. I wish I had bought shares in cardboard-making companies!

@Andrzej
I get tons of mail delivered every single day. And 99.9% is either charitable donation requests, or now, during primary season, mailers from every candidate for every office that's up for re-election, including countless judges whose names are meaningless. They all go straight into the garbage. There's an occasional bill, only because I like to have paper copies in front of me to remind me to pay them. I can't use autopay for the ones that vary from month to month. What makes it even more aggravating is that we all have small cluster boxes here, even the mansions, and some of those mailing are gigantic envelopes or pieces of cardboard that don't even fit in the box.

When I was a kid, mail was delivered twice a day through a slot in the door to the house by the same avuncular gentleman whom we called Uncle Miltie. But that's back in the stone age, when people wrote letters to each other. Now we don't even have a regular carrier, and that's why some important stuff goes missing, and in the rare even that one absolutely has to write a check, it's likely to get stolen.

@Ιασων

Sigh. I expected more of you than low-blow Polish stereotypes 😢



(Which makes *you* posting *this* particularly funny 🤣)

@Heidi
I literally get junk mail about the importance of recycling.

It makes me want to scream.

@Heidi

At least 90% of my daily mail delivery goes straight into the trash, too, but occasionally, there's an unexpected large check from a tax overpayment or a health insurance reimbursement or such.  

So you can bet you life I look at every piece of mail I get!

@Steve L

Check!

My wife and I were amazed in the US in 2011 and 2013 when we realized checks were still a thing. I've last seen a check book in Poland in the 1990s, I think.

@Andrzej
I never call appetizers "APPS." That's just cringey.

As for the mail, it does still come daily, but it's all junk: political ads, coupons for Little Caesar's, pleas from my bank to open a credit card. The occasional auto warranty scam. I wish there was a magic wand I could wave to keep this literal garbage out of my mailbox.

@MExpat

I don't mind nicknames for close family members and pets - there is usually history there, even lore, something that builds our identity as a close-knit group of people (and animals). I rarely address my wife by her name, and vice versa.

Nicknames of other people often irk me though. One of our top footballers had a really siIIy one, and commentators would spam it during every match, making my ears bleed. Ditto one of the best Polish track runners. Argh!

@Jerry

Hahaha! Yeah, I agree that they are no longer considered appropriate.  Still, it cracked me up to write them. If that makes me inappropriate, so be it!  

And thanks so much for your kind thoughts and encouragement! I really appreciate it!! This has been absolutely exhausting and heartbreaking, but I'm happy that we are able to help.  ☺️

@DocP Decades ago my ex pat friends and I in Geneva for some reason shortened Bon Appetit to Beau Knapp.  Somehow helped us deal with our modest French.  Now also the name of a Hollywood actor.

So helped me with this clue.

We also called the Pont Mont Blanc the Po Mo Blo.  Brought Geneva down to Earth.  Same with Jay Doe for the Jet d’Eau.

@DocP
As one in the Food Service Economy, I can reliably state that everyone calls appetizers "apps," at least in the back of the house, if not to the customers.

Even my former boss, who moved to Detroit from Calgary, called them "apps."

@DocP

"No one, ever, calls an appetizer an app."  

And for the nonillionth time a commenter extrapolates their knowledge to the rest of the world, and is embarrassingly wrong.

@Helen Wright

Agreed about the difficulty. But today is Tuesday, even across the pond.  ;-)

Spring Bank Holiday yesterday?

@Helen Wright
It's a Tuesday puzzle, not a Monday. Seems you can't handle the Somerset cider, either 😁.

Congrats on your daughter's wedding!

